"1419","1 January 1440":"1 januari 1440","1439":"1439","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Belgrave, Leicestershire, England":"Belgrave, Leicestershire, England"},"en":{"1419–1468":"1419–1468","1420–1495":"1420–1495","1440–1530":"1440–1530","1397–Male":"1397–Deceased","1400–Female":"1400–Deceased","1468":"1468","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1530":"1530","1420":"1420","1397":"1397","1440":"1440","1495":"1495","1419":"1419","1 January 1440":"1 January 1440","1439":"1439","England":"England, United Kingdom","Belgrave, Leicestershire, England":"Belgrave, Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Belgrave","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Leicestershire, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Merdegrave</i>. The original name derived from Old English <i>mearth</i> ‘marten’ + <i>grāf</i> ‘grove’, but after the Norman Conquest the first element was taken to be Old French <i>merde</i> ‘dung, filth’, and changed to Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’, to remove the unpleasant association. A mid 12th-century writer refers to the place as ‘<i>Merthegrave, nunc</i> (now) <i>Belegrava</i>’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":36,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William de Belgrave was born in 1419, in Belgrave, Leicestershire, England, his father, John Belgrave, was 22 and his mother, Isobel Sandon, was 19. He married Marjory de Willoughby in 1439, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1468, in his hometown, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1419–1468":"1419–1468","1420–1495":"1420–1495","1440–1530":"1440–1530","1397–Male":"1397–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1468":"1468","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1530":"1530","1420":"1420","1397":"1397","1440":"1440","1495":"1495","1419":"1419","1 January 1440":"1. jaanuar 1440","1439":"1439","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Belgrave, Leicestershire, England":"Belgrave, Leicester